WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:02.150
So, hi.

00:00:02.280 --> 00:00:03.320
I'm Matt.

00:00:03.460 --> 00:00:09.150
My main thing I do, I'm on the core Ast

00:00:09.170 --> 00:00:10.800
ro team for the Astro Web Framework.

00:00:10.810 --> 00:00:13.610
I also work at Cloudflare, but I'm not

00:00:13.630 --> 00:00:16.450
here to talk about any of that today.

00:00:16.570 --> 00:00:19.790
I'm here to talk about Cirrus, which is my

00:00:19.790 --> 00:00:20.420
PDS.

00:00:24.310 --> 00:00:27.430
So, I have built a PDS that I use to

00:00:27.430 --> 00:00:31.610
help self-host, and I hopefully might convince some of

00:00:31.610 --> 00:00:33.460
you people here to self-host your PDS as well

00:00:33.470 --> 00:00:33.660
.

00:00:33.670 --> 00:00:41.740
But first, what is a PDS?

00:00:41.750 --> 00:00:46.750
PDS is a personal data server.

00:00:46.770 --> 00:00:51.060
It is where all of your stuff is on the AppR

00:00:51.060 --> 00:00:52.780
oto network.

00:00:52.990 --> 00:00:56.610
Now, a lot of people here probably know this, but

00:00:56.860 --> 00:01:00.520
your PDS holds pretty much everything on the AppRoto

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:02.120
network for you.

00:01:02.150 --> 00:01:06.200
It's all of your posts, of course, but it

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:11.560
's also all of your likes and your friends and your whole

00:01:11.620 --> 00:01:14.930
social graph, but it's also everything from any of your

00:01:15.160 --> 00:01:17.690
other third-party apps that you're working with.

00:01:18.090 --> 00:01:20.920
All of the different network, all of the things on the

00:01:21.030 --> 00:01:23.020
AppRoto network live on your PDS.

00:01:23.030 --> 00:01:25.420
They also, all of the blobs live on there as

00:01:25.420 --> 00:01:27.860
well, which are, you know, the files, the

00:01:28.040 --> 00:01:30.660
images, and the videos, and things like that.

00:01:31.310 --> 00:01:35.370
So, the whole point of a PDS is to make

00:01:35.370 --> 00:01:41.860
it so that you are able to have the network as decentralized

00:01:41.860 --> 00:01:44.540
, so that you own all of your data.

00:01:46.470 --> 00:01:50.010
And what I didn't realize is, as well as being

00:01:50.350 --> 00:01:54.010
where all your data is, it's also where you talk

00:01:54.010 --> 00:01:54.600
to.

00:01:54.830 --> 00:01:56.960
So, it's where your API calls go when you're

00:01:57.200 --> 00:01:58.140
using the network.

00:01:58.230 --> 00:02:01.720
So, when you've got the, like, Blue Sky

00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:05.520
app, for example, on your phone or on the web

00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:08.890
, it's not talking to Blue Sky when it's connected

00:02:08.890 --> 00:02:09.000
.

00:02:09.230 --> 00:02:11.210
If you look at the network panel, and honestly, I

00:02:11.210 --> 00:02:13.160
mean, the first time I knew this was when I opened

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:15.300
up the network panel and saw that it was hitting my PDF

00:02:15.300 --> 00:02:15.480
.

00:02:16.010 --> 00:02:17.730
You talk directly to your PDS.

00:02:17.930 --> 00:02:23.220
So, all of your connections and everything go directly to your

00:02:23.220 --> 00:02:23.860
PDS.

00:02:23.870 --> 00:02:27.180
So, most of the stuff a PDS does is talking

00:02:27.300 --> 00:02:28.160
to you.

00:02:28.170 --> 00:02:33.140
This, obviously, your PDS doesn't have all of

00:02:33.180 --> 00:02:34.940
the data on it.

00:02:34.950 --> 00:02:37.580
Most of the data on the network is somewhere else.

00:02:37.590 --> 00:02:40.410
So, for anything that it doesn't have, like all

00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:44.710
of your timeline and everything else, it proxies it

00:02:44.770 --> 00:02:48.240
to the app view, which, you know, in most

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:51.390
cases is Blue Sky, which holds everything.

00:02:51.570 --> 00:02:56.060
But how does the relay, how does Blue Sky or the

00:02:56.570 --> 00:02:59.730
rest of the network get your data?

00:02:59.930 --> 00:03:02.070
It's done through a relay.

00:03:02.170 --> 00:03:04.820
So, there are two relays that Blue Sky has,

00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:05.000
U.

00:03:05.110 --> 00:03:05.390
S.

00:03:05.390 --> 00:03:06.180
East and U.

00:03:06.180 --> 00:03:06.460
S.

00:03:06.460 --> 00:03:07.070
West.

00:03:07.090 --> 00:03:09.540
They recently changed them around.

00:03:09.950 --> 00:03:13.430
And, basically, your PDS, when you publish something

00:03:13.430 --> 00:03:15.520
, it sends it out to the relay.

00:03:15.530 --> 00:03:18.340
So, the way that works is it's a web socket

00:03:18.400 --> 00:03:20.800
, like a permanent web socket.

00:03:20.810 --> 00:03:23.770
The relay connects to your web socket, and it's,

00:03:23.770 --> 00:03:28.440
whenever you post something, it sends it out into the relay

00:03:28.630 --> 00:03:28.970
.

00:03:29.870 --> 00:03:32.670
And, as you can probably see from this at the moment

00:03:32.740 --> 00:03:35.450
, it's not actually doing a huge amount of work,

00:03:35.450 --> 00:03:36.900
the PDS, per person.

00:03:36.910 --> 00:03:39.580
It's only doing something when you post on it or when

00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:40.960
you make a query on it.

00:03:41.210 --> 00:03:45.050
Because the app view isn't, so when somebody goes and

00:03:45.110 --> 00:03:48.840
looks at your timeline, they aren't hitting your PDS

00:03:49.030 --> 00:03:49.260
.

00:03:49.270 --> 00:03:52.380
What they're doing is it's being relayed to the

00:03:52.380 --> 00:03:54.320
app view from the relays.

00:03:54.330 --> 00:03:58.680
And the relays hold every single post on the network.

00:03:58.690 --> 00:04:04.250
Every single record, every single event on the network goes through

00:04:04.250 --> 00:04:06.820
the relays, and they send it off to the app

00:04:06.820 --> 00:04:07.260
view.

00:04:07.350 --> 00:04:09.070
So, all of the work, really, the heavy work

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:10.850
, is done by the relays and the app view.

00:04:10.870 --> 00:04:14.440
So, it's a PDS, doesn't actually do

00:04:14.440 --> 00:04:18.500
a huge amount of work, but, and you can,

00:04:18.670 --> 00:04:22.780
anyone can host them, but that's not what people are

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:23.430
doing.

00:04:23.470 --> 00:04:26.060
So, you know, 99 point, this, I mean

