00:24:09.810 --> 00:24:13.120
And then there's the fire hose.

00:24:13.190 --> 00:24:16.440
Now, the fire hose is the thing that makes it really

00:24:16.440 --> 00:24:19.540
difficult to host a PDS on a serverless platform in

00:24:19.810 --> 00:24:20.680
most cases.

00:24:20.690 --> 00:24:24.000
So, you can't put it on like an AWS Lambda

00:24:24.120 --> 00:24:30.710
or something like that because it needs a continuously connected web socket

00:24:30.870 --> 00:24:31.070
.

00:24:32.530 --> 00:24:35.220
The actual thing that made me, like, decide to build

00:24:35.220 --> 00:24:37.860
this was when I heard about, found out that you could

00:24:37.860 --> 00:24:40.600
do hibernating web sockets on durable objects.

00:24:40.610 --> 00:24:44.590
What that means is that you can have a web socket on

00:24:44.590 --> 00:24:47.970
this, on this PDS that is open all the time

00:24:47.970 --> 00:24:51.380
and connected to the relay all the time.

00:24:51.870 --> 00:24:55.180
But you're not paying unless you are sending an event.

00:24:55.290 --> 00:24:58.160
If there is nothing going from it, it just goes to

00:24:58.230 --> 00:24:58.830
sleep.

00:24:58.850 --> 00:25:00.280
It hibernates it.

00:25:00.290 --> 00:25:01.890
But as far as the relay is concerned, it's still

00:25:01.890 --> 00:25:02.430
connected.

00:25:02.470 --> 00:25:04.860
It thinks that it's connected, but it's actually just

00:25:04.860 --> 00:25:06.900
being held by, you know, some part of our Cloud

00:25:06.920 --> 00:25:08.320
flow infra or something.

00:25:08.330 --> 00:25:10.460
But when you then want to add, send an event,

00:25:10.700 --> 00:25:13.200
when you're posting something, it wakes it up and p

00:25:13.340 --> 00:25:15.800
ings it off onto the relay and you get charged for a

00:25:15.800 --> 00:25:16.720
few seconds.

00:25:17.090 --> 00:25:19.100
Well, you don't get charged because it will be within

00:25:19.100 --> 00:25:21.060
the free tier unless, I think, even the craziest of

00:25:21.060 --> 00:25:22.990
posters won't be able to get outside the free tier on

00:25:22.990 --> 00:25:23.350
this one.

00:25:23.590 --> 00:25:26.870
And then it uses R2 for storing all the blobs

00:25:26.870 --> 00:25:27.160
.

00:25:27.190 --> 00:25:29.330
That's all still inside Cloudflare.

00:25:29.430 --> 00:25:31.840
And then it proxies it to the app view,

00:25:31.840 --> 00:25:34.440
which is, you know, wherever it is.

00:25:34.450 --> 00:25:37.940
And I didn't show you a few things.

00:25:37.950 --> 00:25:40.500
So there's account migration, which is built in.

00:25:40.510 --> 00:25:41.500
So that was one of the things.

00:25:41.510 --> 00:25:44.100
I didn't want you to have to use any third-

00:25:44.100 --> 00:25:46.920
party service, however good they are.

00:25:46.970 --> 00:25:50.510
I wanted it to all be just done through this Create PD

00:25:50.510 --> 00:25:51.450
S workflow.

00:25:51.630 --> 00:25:53.760
So if you are using, if you are migrating something

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:55.980
, you will move over to where, you know, it

00:25:55.980 --> 00:25:57.880
will take you through a different flow.

00:25:58.030 --> 00:26:01.120
You'll put in your password and it will migrate everything.

00:26:01.130 --> 00:26:02.850
It will download it all and then upload it.

00:26:03.010 --> 00:26:05.730
And then it will help you do the PLC, the

00:26:05.730 --> 00:26:09.110
did PLC migration and all that kind of stuff.

00:26:09.130 --> 00:26:11.100
It uses passkeys for most stuff.

00:26:11.110 --> 00:26:13.410
I was going to demo passkeys, but it sticks a

00:26:13.480 --> 00:26:15.540
bloody great QR code up on the screen.

00:26:16.850 --> 00:26:18.120
So I was like, no, this is probably not the

00:26:18.120 --> 00:26:18.960
best way of doing that.

00:26:18.970 --> 00:26:22.890
But that's something I'm particularly pleased with because to add

00:26:22.890 --> 00:26:25.230
a passkey on there, it does a QR code in

00:26:25.590 --> 00:26:28.740
the terminal that you can use to scan it.

00:26:28.770 --> 00:26:30.490
And that works for all of the, you know, all

00:26:30.490 --> 00:26:32.490
the third-party services and everything.

00:26:34.610 --> 00:26:38.200
So this is a personal data server.

00:26:38.350 --> 00:26:39.000
This is the thing.

00:26:39.010 --> 00:26:41.680
This is you can build one for yourself.

00:26:41.690 --> 00:26:46.630
And I think there are, I think that there's a

00:26:46.700 --> 00:26:52.000
, you know, most people do want to have their PD

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:54.580
S hosted by Blue Sky.

00:26:55.010 --> 00:26:56.900
You know, that's where it makes sense to do it

00:26:56.960 --> 00:26:57.120
.

00:26:57.130 --> 00:27:00.400
But I think that if we want the app proto network to

00:27:00.400 --> 00:27:04.760
be properly decentralized, we need to have lots of different ways

00:27:04.930 --> 00:27:05.880
of hosting.

00:27:05.890 --> 00:27:08.560
And I think that, you know, it needs to be

00:27:08.560 --> 00:27:11.420
easy for a service to have their own PDS.

00:27:11.610 --> 00:27:14.240
You know, one of the, any of these other services

00:27:14.240 --> 00:27:16.040
can provide it for their users.

00:27:16.130 --> 00:27:18.940
They want, and, but I think there also needs to

00:27:18.940 --> 00:27:22.120
be an easy way for people to deploy it themselves.

00:27:22.450 --> 00:27:25.970
And I think that one of the things that I really love

00:27:26.270 --> 00:27:29.250
about this group of all of us, you know, weird

00:27:29.250 --> 00:27:33.030
os and most affectionately here is that it reminds me a

00:27:33.030 --> 00:27:34.960
lot of early web stuff.

00:27:34.970 --> 00:27:37.710
And one of the whole things about the early web is that

00:27:37.710 --> 00:27:40.330
you could, you know, deploy your own stuff and do

00:27:40.330 --> 00:27:43.720
all kinds of, and I think that the fact that all

00:27:43.990 --> 00:27:50.420
of the reference architecture of the atmosphere is blue sky stuff.

00:27:51.290 --> 00:27:54.830
It means that it's, you know, very much angled

00:27:54.830 --> 00:27:58.750
, not just towards the social use case, but also to

00:27:58.750 --> 00:28:00.430
the massive scale.

00:28:00.450 --> 00:28:03.750
And it's great that people are building all these other different

00:28:03.760 --> 00:28:04.880
implementations.

00:28:04.930 --> 00:28:08.230
But I think that we need more ways for people to just

00:28:08.280 --> 00:28:11.960
make this as easy as, you know, sticking something on

00:28:11.960 --> 00:28:14.280
Netlify or Vercel or Cloudflare or

00:28:14.280 --> 00:28:17.120
whatever, whatever you think of them.

00:28:17.130 --> 00:28:19.280
They are a very, very easy way of putting a website

00:28:19.460 --> 00:28:19.700
up.

00:28:19.710 --> 00:28:22.420
And I wanted this to be a way to make it that

00:28:22.420 --> 00:28:23.940
easy to put a PDF up.

00:28:23.950 --> 00:28:26.670
So hopefully some people will try this out.

00:28:26.690 --> 00:28:28.820
Follow me.

00:28:28.950 --> 00:28:33.430
Follow my 15 other variations of this that I used over the

00:28:33.890 --> 00:28:36.580
past week while I've been practicing.

00:28:36.650 --> 00:28:39.620
I'm sure they're all going to have really useful things

00:28:39.620 --> 00:28:40.190
to say.

00:28:40.230 --> 00:28:41.950
And thank you, everybody.

00:28:41.990 --> 00:28:45.480
One minute.
